          "body": "The final movement of the chapter is the most formally demanding: three months of investigation (10:16-17) followed by a list of 111 named men who had married foreign wives (10:18-43), closed by the stark summary of 10:44. The name-list is not narrative padding. It is the chapter's — and the book's — most serious pastoral statement: covenant faithfulness is not a general principle but a personal accounting. Each name represents a man, a wife, a family, and a decision. The list begins with the sons of the high-priestly line (sons of Jeshua son of Jozadak, 10:18) — the very family whose restoration was the linchpin of the community's cultic life. That the priestly house is listed first and most specifically signals that the chapter will not exempt the leadership from the same standard applied to the people. The guilt offering of a ram (10:19) connects the priests' pledge to the Levitical guilt-offering system of Leviticus 5-6: sin against what belongs to God requires sacrificial atonement, not merely behavioral correction. The chapter closes with 10:44's unanswered reality: 'some of them had wives by whom they had children.' The text does not tell us what happened to those children; it does not resolve the human wreckage the covenant breach has created. This canonical silence is not an oversight. It is an honest witness that obedience to God's covenant can be simultaneously right and painful, and that Scripture does not always tidy the human cost of sin's consequences."
